definitions.definition: ( less common in the US and Canada ) A sweet mixture of fruit boiled with sugar and allowed to congeal. Often spread on bread or toast or used in jam tarts .

subdefinitions.definition: ( countable , baseball ) A difficult situation for a pitcher or defending team.
examples: The pitcher's in a jam now, having walked the bases loaded with the cleanup hitter coming to bat.

definitions.definition: ( countable ) A blockage , congestion , or immobilization .
examples: a jam on the 101 South, blocking the two right lanes [radio report]
a jam of logs in a river

definitions.definition: ( countable , popular music ) An informal, impromptu performance or rehearsal.
( countable , by extension , informal ) A song ; a track .
( countable , by extension ) An informal event where people brainstorm and collaborate on projects .
examples: We came up with some new ideas at the game jam .

definitions.definition: ( countable , slang ) That which one particularly prefers, desires, enjoys, or cares about.
( countable , roller derby ) A play during which points can be scored.
examples: Toughie scored four points in that jam .

definitions.definition: ( countable , climbing ) Any of several manoeuvres requiring wedging of an extremity into a tight space.
examples: I used a whole series of fist and foot jams in that crack.

definitions.definition: ( Australia ) The tree Acacia acuminata , with fruity-smelling hard timber.
( UK , slang ) Luck hence jammy - lucky.
examples: He's got more jam than Waitrose.

definitions.definition: ( Canada , slang ) balls , bollocks , courage , machismo
examples: I don't think he has the jam .

definitions.definition: ( slang ) Sexual relations or the contemplation of them.
( slang ) Something enjoyable; a delightful situation or outcome.
